english:
  title: Epitaph for Lord Yun of Haepyeong, Posthumously Titled Chunggan
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Yun clan of Haepyeong in Seonsan is a family of great renown. One ancestor, whose name was Kun-jeong, served Kings Go and Won, rising to the rank of Grand Commandant of the Golden Purple, Minister of Works, and Left Deputy Chancellor. Another, named Man-bi, served King Chungnyeol and became a First-Class Merit Subject, ending his career as Vice Director of the Secret Secretariat. And there was one named Seok, the Premier, who once stood before the king as a wine-server when an envoy from Yuan arrived. The envoy delivered the imperial edict commanding the two princes to attend the Yuan court. Upon hearing this, the Premier thought to himself, "I should follow my younger brother." He returned home and told his father, who replied, "Your plan is mistaken. One follows a prince for future advantage. How can the younger brother possess the realm while the elder still lives?" The Premier replied, "I understand that well. Yet when I see my younger brother, respect stirs in my heart, but not so with my elder. This is why I have decided thus." His father said no more. The elder brother, the Crown Prince, died young, while the younger became King Chungseok. When the Premier followed the prince to the Yuan capital, none among his colleagues surpassed him. Later he rose to Right Premier and Chief of the Bureau of Rites, was enfeoffed as Lord of Haepyeong, and bore the rank of Grand Commandant of the Three Han Kingdoms, receiving the title of Meritorious Subject for Loyalty, Integrity, Harmony, and Virtuous Aid. None surpassed him, and surely such harmony between sovereign and minister comes but once in a thousand years—is this not Heaven's design?

    After this, when the Son of Heaven heard of his renown, he specially appointed him Grand General Who Pacifies the Nation and Supreme Commander of Goryeo, honoring him greatly. The Lord of Haepyeong married the daughter of Yi Baek-nyon, an official of high rank. In the fourth month of the cyclical year Gyeongseul of Zhida, a son was born—our subject. In the cyclical year Gyeongsin of Yanyou, at age eleven, he was appointed to the True Rank in Taeyun Temple. At fifteen, he received the office of True Director of Bureau of Ceremonies. At sixteen, he was made a Commandant. At nineteen, he was appointed Grand Guard, the year after he went to Yuan with the Crown Prince. At this time, the Prince of Jin passed away. Emperor Wenzong, coming first from the south, ascended to the throne, then welcomed Ming-zong from the north. When Wenzong went out to greet him, the Chancellor Yan Tie-mu-er presented poisoned wine. Ming-zong died in the night, and the Six Armies fell into chaos. Our subject, together with Chancellor Cao Yi-cheong, Yi Gun-hae, and other officials, supported the Crown Prince, who thus had no fear and was granted an iron charter of merit.

    In the cyclical year Gyeonggo of Zhishun, he was promoted to Grand Guard at age twenty-one. In the cyclical year Sinsa of Zhizheng, he advanced to Director of the Bureau of Horses. Five months after Ming-zong ascended the throne, he was appointed Grand Guard. In winter, he rose to Director of the Bureau of Military Records. The following April, he transferred to Chief of the Bureau of Rites. The King-Premier was then governing according to the old system: civil appointments went through the Bureau of Rites, military through the Military Bureau. Our subject assisted the Premier with perfect integrity. The next year he was sent out as Governor of Pyeongyang to test his ability in governing the people. Within a single year, his administration bore fruit, and he was recalled as Director of the Secret Secretariat at age thirty-eight. In the fifth year of Emperor Shun's reign, he became Director of the Secret Secretariat a second time. That winter he bore a memorial to the capital, offering thanks for robes bestowed upon him. In the eighteenth year, he held the position a third time. In the cyclical year Gyeongseul of Hongwu, he advanced to Secret Secretariat Official. The next year he became Director of the Bureau of Officials and Overseer of Deliberative Conferences. The year after, he was promoted to Counselor, and in winter was enfeoffed as Grand Commandant and Lord of Haepyeong. He formed a society with the venerable gentlemen Yeom Jok-seong and Yun Chil-won and others, living in tranquility for more than a decade.

    In the ninth month of the cyclical year Imseul, he fell ill. On the ninth day of the tenth month, sitting upright, he passed away at the age of seventy-three. By nature, he was generous and without pretense. He knew something of the Mongol tongue and conducted himself like a man of the northern courts. In affairs of state, he followed the general principles without being petty. He was a man of true cultivation. He took two wives. His first was the daughter of Yeom Yon-su, a Grand Commandant and Esteemed Counselor of the Pavilion of Treasured Writings, posthumously titled Master Wen-keuk. His second was the daughter of the Grand Commandant and Lord of Wolseong. By his first wife he had two sons: the elder, Bao, who rose to Grand Guard and died before him, and the younger, Jin, who became Grand Commandant and Lord of Haepyeong. His grandson Ka-gwan serves as Vice Director of the Secret Secretariat and Deputy Supreme Commander of Gyeongsang Province. His daughters married well into noble houses. His sons by his second wife became officials in various bureaus, and his descendants are numerous.

    When our subject bore the memorial of thanks to the capital, I served as the recording official. His eldest son was my age-mate, and so I served him as a father. Through fortune I entered the Imperial Chancellery, and when our subject was restored to office, we became colleagues. Yet I continued to serve him as before, and he regarded me as a son. How could I not inscribe his tomb? His youngest son, the Premier, has now inherited his titles. When that son served as Director of the Examination Board, he selected my son among his scholars. How could I refuse this honor?

    Thus the inscription:

    The Yun of Haepyeong
    served Kings Go and Won—
    the grace of gentlemen
    flows endless as its spring.

    Grand General emerged
    to become Attendant Chancellor,
    and Chunggan inherited
    the bearing of true cultivation.

    Young and brilliant,
    old and honored,
    the youngest became Premier,
    holding the civil examinations.

    Grandson appointed
    to the inner council,
    defending the coastal realm—
    the house of such a man
    found fortune in the midst of change.

    All blessings Heaven bestows
    make virtue ever bright.
    I speak no flattery of the Lord,
    but he rests eternal in this earth.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Ming-zong (明宗) and Wenzong (文宗) were emperors of Yuan; the incident described involved a succession dispute in which Ming-zong was poisoned by the chancellor Yan Tie-mu-er.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Six Armies' (六軍) refers to the military forces attending the imperial court.
  - key: ''
    value: The iron charter (鐵卷) was a token of merit and immunity granted to high-ranking officials and generals.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'north' (北方/北庭) refers to the Yuan court in Khanbaliq (present-day Beijing).
